metaData.descriptionCS: The examinee is shown, sequentially, two grids with blue and red circles. The examinee is then asked to add or subtract the location of the circles based on a set of rules.

questions.title: Demonstration Item 1
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
Incorrect response:

Say, That’s not quite right. The first grid had a blue circle here (point to the top left), and the second grid had a blue circle here (point to the top right). Put a blue circle where there was a blue circle on either grid.

Remove any blue circles from the grid. Repeat demonstration if needed.
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Say, Now I will combine the two grids I just saw to create a new grid. I will put a blue circle here where I saw a blue circle on the first grid. On the client device, drag a blue circle to the top left corner. And a blue circle here where I saw it on the second grid. On the client device, drag a blue circle to the top right corner.

Remove the blue circles from the grid. Say, Now you try. Put a blue circle where you saw a blue circle on either the first or second grid.

questions.title: Demonstration Item 2
questions.correctInstructionsHTML:
Correct response:

Say, That’s right.
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
Incorrect response:

Say, That’s not quite right. The first grid had a blue circle here and here. Point to top left and top right. The second grid had a blue circle here. Point to top right. There was a blue circle in this place on both grids. Point to the top right square. So put a white circle here. Have the examinee drag a white circle into the top right corner of the grid. There was a blue circle in this place on only one grid. Point to top left. So put a blue circle here. Have the examinee drag a blue circle into the top left corner of the grid.
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Say, Now I will combine the two grids I just saw to create a new grid. I will put a white circle where I saw a blue circle in the same place on both grids. Drag a white circle to the top right corner of the grid on the client device. And I will put a blue circle where I saw a blue circle on only one of the grids. Drag a blue circle to the top left corner of the grid on the client device. 

Say, Do you understand? If the examinee does not understand, go back to the previous screen and show the stimuli again. Provide further instruction if needed.

Remove the circles from the grid on the client device. Say, Now you try. Put a white circle where there was a blue circle in the same place on both grids, and put a blue circle where there was a blue circle in a place on only one of the grids.

questions.title: Sample A
questions.correctInstructionsHTML:
Correct response:

Say, That’s right. You placed a blue circle where there was a blue circle in only one of the grids and a white circle where there was a blue cicle in both grids.

Let’s try another one.
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
Incorrect response:

If the examinee makes an error in placement or appears to not understand, place the circles in the correct locations (refer to the reduced grid above). Say, See, this is how the grid should look. Place a blue circle here (point to the correct location on the grid) because only one of the grids had a blue circle in this place. Place a white circle here (point to the correct location on the grid) because both grids had a blue circle in this place.

Let’s try another one.

consecutiveZerosDiscontinueRule.description: This subtest discontinues after 4 consecutive scores of 0.

reverseRule.noSkipMsg: If suspected of intellectual disability or moderate to severe memory deficits
